	<h1>Maze generation algorithms</h2>
	<p>Here are demonstrated three different algorithms for generating mazes and each maze is solved by a recursive backtracking algorithm.</p>

	<h2>Kruskal's method</h2>
	<p style='border-left: 5px solid blue; padding-left: 10px;'>
	Kruskal's method is normally used for constructing a minimal spanning tree for a graph. It can also be used for making a maze. Start by creating a list of all possible edges and randomly shuffle them iterate over each possible edge and create a corridor in the maze only if both rooms aren't connected by an existing path.
	</p>
	<div id='cont'>
		<canvas style='border: 4px double blue;' id='kruskal_canvas' width='500' height='480'> </canvas>
		<div id='kruskalsrc'></div>
	</div>

	<h2>Recursive backtracking</h2>
	<p style='border-left: 5px solid green; padding-left: 10px;'>Pick a starting cell. Pick one of the surrounding rooms that has not been visited and create an edge between both rooms and mark it as current. Repeat this process until all rooms are visited.</p>
	<div id='cont'>
		<canvas style='border: 4px double green;' id='backtracking_canvas' width='500' height='480'> </canvas>
		<div id='recbacksrc'></div>
	</div>


	<h2>Division method</h2>
	<p style='border-left: 5px solid yellow; padding-left: 10px;'>Split the grid into two halves connected by a single edge. Repeat the process for both rooms until the room becomes too small for division. </p>
	<div id='cont'>
		<canvas style='border: 4px double yellow;' id='division_canvas' width='500' height='480'> </canvas>
		<div id='divmethsrc'></div>
	</div>


